---

🔧 PART 1: VLOOKUP (Vertical Lookup)


---

📌 Structure

=VLOOKUP(lookup_value, table_array, col_index, [range_lookup])


---

🧠 Deep Understanding

lookup_value → what to search

table_array → where to search

col_index → which column to return

range_lookup → exact (FALSE) or approx (TRUE)



---

💻 Example

=VLOOKUP(A2, F2:G3, 2, FALSE)


---

🧠 Step-by-Step Execution

For customer_id = 1:

1. Search 1 in first column of table


2. Found row


3. Return 2nd column → "Vinod"




---

❗ Limitation

👉 Works only left → right
👉 Cannot look backward


---

🔧 PART 2: HLOOKUP (Horizontal Lookup)


---

📌 Structure

=HLOOKUP(lookup_value, table_array, row_index, [range_lookup])


---

🧠 Meaning

👉 Works horizontally (rows) instead of columns


---

💻 Example

ID	1	2

Name	Vinod	Ravi


=HLOOKUP(1, A1:C2, 2, FALSE)


---

🧠 Execution

1. Search 1 in first row


2. Move to 2nd row


3. Return → "Vinod"




---

❗ Reality

👉 Rarely used in real projects
👉 But asked in interviews


---

🔥 PART 3: XLOOKUP (MODERN 🔥🔥)


---

📌 Structure

=XLOOKUP(lookup_value, lookup_array, return_array)


---

💻 Example

=XLOOKUP(A2, F2:F3, G2:G3)


---

🧠 Deep Understanding

lookup_array → where to search

return_array → what to return



---

🎯 Why XLOOKUP is Powerful


---

✅ Works both directions

👉 Left → Right
👉 Right → Left


---

✅ No column index needed

👉 More flexible


---

✅ Handles errors better


---


---

⚡ Step 4: Comparison

Feature	VLOOKUP	HLOOKUP	XLOOKUP

Direction	Vertical	Horizontal	Both
Flexibility	Low	Low	High
Modern	❌	❌	✅



---

🎤 Interview Answer

“Difference between VLOOKUP and XLOOKUP?”

> VLOOKUP searches vertically and requires a column index, while XLOOKUP is more flexible, works in both directions, and does not require a column index.




